(0,1575.94 8.24561e+06,1575.94)Types of Transportation Investment
(0,1575.94 8.49763e+06,1575.94)Future directions in transportation investment can take several paths. Basically
(0,1575.94 8.7394e+06,1575.94)transportation investment encompasses two forms: capital expansion and capital
(870.912,7530.97 391.388,7530.97)Transportation in the New Millennium
(4303.76,0 442.191,0)2
(-5123.52,-437.76 6796.05,-437.76)enhancement. Expansion includes the construction of additional highway segments; rail
(0,-167.04 13301,-167.04)lines; runways; or additional sea air rail or bus terminal capacity using traditional
(0,-164.16 19440,-164.16)technology. Highway examples include the addition of lanes to an Interstate highway
(0,-167.04 26071.2,-167.04)system the conversion of an existing two-lane road to a four-lane limited-access highway
(0,-164.16 32112.9,-164.16)replacement or widening of bridges and the extension of an existing road. Airport
(0,-167.04 38483.9,-167.04)examples include runway lengthening apron (tarmac) expansion and additional terminal
(0,-164.16 38918,-164.16)gates.
(216,-167.04 45233.9,-167.04)Enhancement refers to new technologies that can enhance the efficiency of the existing
(-216,-164.16 51240.8,-164.16)highway system. Examples include intelligent highway systems congestion pricing
(0,-167.04 57544.4,-167.04)intermodal freight facilities geographic positioning systems and instrument landing
(0,-164.16 63531.9,-164.16)systems to mention a few major innovations. Within each of these areas numerous
(0,-167.04 69794.7,-167.04)innovations are being developed. Policy makers and practitioners need to gain a clear
(0,-164.16 75743.4,-164.16)understanding of the effects of these innovations on economic development through
(0,-167.04 82353,-167.04)enhanced delivery of transportation services and a more efficient use of scarce resources.
(0,-164.16 88935.8,-164.16)Scarce resources may extend beyond transportation investment dollars to include land use
(0,-167.04 91383.1,-167.04)air quality and noise pollution.
(216,-164.16 97721.4,-164.16)Moreover highways rail lines airports and seaports should and are being considered
(-216,-167.04 104201,-167.04)as a system where the system goes beyond the fixed infrastructure such as a stretch of
(0,-164.16 110867,-164.16)highway or a rail line to include the vehicles that use the infrastructure. The concept of
(0,-167.04 117426,-167.04)intelligent highway systems underscores this trend. Simply put vehicles are being linked
(0,-164.16 124092,-164.16)to each other and to traffic control devices to improve the efficiency of the total highway
(0,-167.04 130936,-167.04)system. Similar types of innovations in intelligent traffic management are emerging for air
(0,-164.16 132552,-164.16)sea and rail systems.
(216,-167.04 138672,-167.04)One important area of research is to explore the productivity-enhancing innovations
(-216,-164.16 140966,-164.16)that are being introduced into 
(1733.76,0 145297,0)existing transport systems. A framework should be provided
(-1733.76,-167.04 151687,-167.04)and benchmarks should be established for understanding the broad economic consequences
(0,-164.16 157971,-164.16)of these innovations. To be assured that research encompasses the issues important to
(0,-167.04 161049,-167.04)decision makers in the new millennium a 
(2439.36,0 164312,0)systemwide and regional economic perspective
(-2439.36,-164.16 170755,-164.16)will have to be maintained. Researchers must be mindful of the direct social effects of
(0,-167.04 175038,-167.04)transportation investment as well as the economic effects.
(216,-164.16 180863,-164.16)Researchers should not neglect the more fundamental issues of understanding the
(-216,-167.04 187306,-167.04)effects of different attributes of highways on economic development. That is do we know
(0,-164.16 193599,-164.16)anything about the effects on productivity of reducing highway congestion or improving
