(0,-334.08 26452.4,-334.08)Data
(0,-161.28 32880.2,-161.28)Acquiring accurate and comprehensive data on a regular basis is a perennial problem for
(0,-167.04 39580.8,-167.04)analysts and policy makers. There is a sizable gap between data that are available and data
(0,-164.16 40241.7,-164.16)required 
(515.52,0 46170.1,0)to answer the questions raised by decision makers. A glaring gap in most studies
(-515.52,-167.04 52828.3,-167.04)is the lack of information on the flows of goods and people. Most analyses of the relation
(0,-164.16 59268,-164.16)between transportation investment and economic productivity do not take into account the
(0,-167.04 65903.5,-167.04)intensity of use of transportation systems. Productivity studies particularly those using
(0,-164.16 72463,-164.16)production and cost function frameworks typically treat all transportation systems as if
(0,-167.04 79058.3,-167.04)traffic flows are the same. This simplified assumption potentially leads to biases in the
(0,-164.16 85447.6,-164.16)estimates of the productivity of transportation infrastructure. Moreover this approach
(0,-167.04 91417.1,-167.04)ignores the very activity—shipment of goods—that generates the productivity gains.
(216,-164.16 97957.9,-164.16)Another deficiency in data collection is the lack of information that links the location
(-216,-167.04 104347,-167.04)of businesses and households to the location of the transportation systems that provide
(0,-164.16 110935,-164.16)them with services. Most productivity studies are conducted using data that are aggregated
(0,-167.04 117565,-167.04)by some level of government jurisdiction. Studies performed at the state or national level
(0,-164.16 124285,-164.16)fall far short of establishing a spatial link. It is likely that state-level analyses could
(0,-167.04 130674,-167.04)attribute the efficiency gains experienced by a business in one part of the state to an
(0,-164.16 137410,-164.16)Interstate highway located in another part of the state. The problem is even more acute for
(0,-167.04 144093,-167.04)national-level studies. Furthermore estimates from state-level analyses do not address the
(0,-164.16 150743,-164.16)questions that policy makers or planners have to consider concerning the location and type
(0,-167.04 152165,-167.04)of future projects.
(216,-164.16 158356,-164.16)Among regional and corridor studies the links between highway benefits and patterns
(-216,-167.04 165021,-167.04)of use are typically developed but the net productivity effect is often not measured. Such
(0,-164.16 171736,-164.16)studies tend to pay more attention to gross levels of job and income attraction than to the
(0,-167.04 174645,-167.04)measurement of net productivity effects.
(216,-164.16 180666,-164.16)One important direction in coming years is to explore better ways to generate and
(-216,-167.04 187223,-167.04)collect the data necessary to conduct useful studies. Because important effects go beyond
(0,-164.16 193943,-164.16)the outcomes of the transportation system itself many types of data are needed. These data
(0,-167.04 200301,-167.04)include transportation system characteristics employment firm-level characteristics
(0,-164.16 206797,-164.16)transportation financing information commodity flows and accompanying characteristics
(0,-167.04 213189,-167.04)of the regions included in the economic analysis. Furthermore the data should be both
(0,-164.16 218624,-164.16)cross section and time series to improve the reliability of the estimates.
(216,-167.04 221768,-167.04)One way to generate data is to educate the 
(2468.16,0 224577,0)decision makers and those in charge of
(-2684.16,-164.16 231298,-164.16)operating the transportation systems as to the importance of such analysis and its value to
(0,-167.04 238024,-167.04)them in carrying out their responsibilities. The approach may prove particularly useful for
(0,-164.16 243057,-164.16)generating administrative data but may also help in collecting more 
